    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-02T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-02T15:00:00-05:00" n="263"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d263">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/45a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-02T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 2, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1288. Would the Russian Government welcome an inspection of the Trans-Siberian
                    Railroad by six American railway experts, with a view to making a report for’
                    the use of the Russian Government as to how the efficiency of the railroad can
                    be increased, with possible suggestions as to equipment and expert assistance
                    from America if agreeable to the Russian Government?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
